# Device UI Agent -- MeetingBox Kivy Touchscreen

## Domain
You own the Kivy-based OLED touchscreen UI under `device-ui/src/`. This runs on a Raspberry Pi 5 with a 3.5" OLED display.

## Architecture
- **Kivy 2.3+** GUI framework with SDL2 backend
- Connects to the web service backend via **httpx** (async HTTP) and **websockets**
- Screen manager handles navigation between screens
- Designed for 480x320 resolution touchscreen

## Key Files
- `main.py` -- Kivy app entry, screen manager, WebSocket listener
- `config.py` -- Colors, fonts, sizes, backend URLs, display settings
- `api_client.py` -- Async HTTP client for backend API
- `mock_backend.py` -- Mock backend for development/testing
- `screens/` -- All screen classes (home, recording, meetings, settings, WiFi, etc.)
- `components/` -- Reusable widgets (button, card, status_bar, modal, etc.)

## Screen Flow
Splash -> Welcome -> WiFi Setup -> Setup Progress -> All Set -> Home
Home -> Recording -> Processing -> Complete
Home -> Meetings -> Meeting Detail
Home -> Settings -> WiFi / System / Pickers

## Backend API Dependency
The device UI calls these backend endpoints:
- `GET/POST /api/meetings/*` -- recording control, meeting list/detail
- `GET/PATCH /api/device/settings` -- device settings
- `GET /api/device/wifi/scan`, `POST /api/device/wifi/connect` -- WiFi
- `GET /api/system/status` -- system info
- `WS /ws` -- real-time events

## Coding Standards
- Always cancel Clock events and scheduled callbacks in `on_leave()` or cleanup methods
- Use try/finally for resource cleanup
- Reference colors from `config.COLORS` dict -- never hardcode hex values
- Handle API errors gracefully with user-visible feedback
- Use `self.app.screen_manager` for navigation, not `self.manager`
- All async operations must handle connection errors and timeouts
- Test with mock backend before testing against real backend
